  "prompt": "How is the M27 IAR issued at the US Marines squad level? One for each fire-team, or mixed with the M249 SAW?",
  "response": "The M27 Infantry Automatic Rifle (IAR) is typically issued at the squad level in the U.S. Marine Corps as part of their infantry units. Originally, the concept was to replace the M249 Squad Automatic Weapon (SAW) with the M27 in a more streamlined role. This transition meant that each fire team within a squad would be equipped with an M27 IAR, resulting in four M27s per squad: one for each of the three fire teams and one with the squad leader or another member, depending on the unit's specific organization and needs.\n\nThe idea was to enhance the automatic rifleman's role with a more accurate, lightweight, and versatile weapon, emphasizing precision and maneuverability. However, the specific allocation can vary depending on the needs of the unit, operational demands, and ongoing evaluations of the weapons in different roles. Some units might still deploy a mix depending on their mission profiles, but generally, the M27 has been largely intended to replace the M249 in many infantry roles.",
